Yes, the Firebase Emulators do not require real credentials in most cases. Instead, they automatically use emulated credentials. The exception to this is if your rules or Cloud Functions code reference other projects using `admin.initializeApp()`.

In other words, if you're just working with a regularly initialized Firebase app (i.e., you've used `firebase.initializeApp()` without any params), the emulators will automatically connect to the right place.

```javascript
const firebase = require('firebase');
// Do NOT pass anything to initializeApp in testing
firebase.initializeApp();
```
If your code requires access to a real Firebase project, for example, to validate custom tokens, then you might need to provide real credentials while using emulators.

This can be done using service account credentials downloaded from your Firebase project settings:

```javascript
var admin = require('firebase-admin');
var serviceAccount = require('path/to/serviceAccountKey.json');

admin.initializeApp({
  credential: admin.credential.cert(serviceAccount)
});
```

You should make sure to secure your service account credentials and avoid exposing them in publicly accessible locations.

